{
  "answer": "**Charles Comte recounts this story in *Traité de Législation: VOL III*, Chapter 49 (\"Du penchant à la servitude et de quelques autres vices attribués aux peuples d’espèces colorées. — Du droit que les blancs ont sur les noirs\").**[^1]\n\nThere, he describes slaves in Louisiana who, under benevolent masters permitting them to accumulate a *peculium*, use their savings as children to purchase freedom for their elderly parents. In the same paragraph, he notes: \"At the time of the insurrection of Saint-Domingue, there were slaves who, out of pity for their masters, renounced the liberty they could acquire, and accompanied them in their flight to the United States.\" He adds the ironic \"reward\": **\"The masters rewarded them by selling them to the first slave traders who presented themselves.\"**[^1]\n\n[^1]: Charles Comte, *Traité de Législation: VOL III*, [paragraph](/works/charles-comte-traite-de-legislation-vol-iii-ca589a/49-du-penchant-a-la-servitude-et-de-quelques-autres-v/translation/#p-b0a33a).",
